If signs are localized to the spinal column, take spinal radiographs to look for possible fractures or bone abnormalities, such as proliferative or lytic lesions. Myelography is useful for localizing lesions of the spinal cord and determining a site for surgical approach if needed (see Fig. 10-3
). If possible, perform a spinal tap to obtain a sample of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) for analysis. Sites for CSF tap and myelography are the atlanto-occipital and the lumbar (L5-L6) regions. Use a 25-gauge spinal needle, as in canine and feline myelography; a suggested contrast medium is iohexol at 0.25 to 0.5 mL/kg50 (Fig. 10-4
). Reference values for CSF fluid analysis are total protein 28 to 68 μg/μL and nucleated cells 0 to 8/μL.37 Some spinal lesions may be amenable to surgical resection or stabilization; many, however, carry a poor prognosis.
